      "identifier": "session-client-state-transition-inconsistency",
      "summary": "Client connection state transitions keep inactive placeholders and skip normalization, producing mixed semantics in auth-state transitions.",
      "related_files": [
        "goseg/session/ws.go"
      ],
      "evidence": [
        "`transitionClientStateLocked` has a fast-path for `targetAuth && !client.Active` that appends a client and returns without setting active state, creating a branch with different semantics from the normal transition path.",
        "`enqueueFakeConnIfNilOrUnconnected` explicitly inserts placeholder `MuConn` values, and cleanup/transition logic then has to special-case inactive/nil connections, increasing state-machine ambiguity.",
        "The result is a brittle mix of transport lifecycle, placeholder management, and auth-state transitions in the same function, which is hard to reason about and extend safely."
      ],
      "suggestion": "Refactor `ClientManager` state updates around a single explicit transition function that always normalizes `(connection, active, bucket)` as an invariant and remove placeholder insertion from auth-state transitions. Represent temporary pending sessions separately from active session buckets to keep transition logic coherent.",
